      <hedline>
        <hl1>Between the Conventions, Lieberman Is Topic A</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Aron P Goldfeld letter on Aug 9 editorial agrees Gore-Lieberman campaign should not adopt tone reminiscent of Republicans' courtship of religious right</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Revival Time in Nashville'' (editorial, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>While I agree that Al Gore's choice of Joseph I. Lieberman as his running mate was a good one, I think you correctly point out that it is imperative that the Gore-Lieberman campaign and the Democratic Party not take on a tone that reminds voters of the Republicans' courtship of the religious right.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Revival Time in Nashville'' (editorial, Aug. 9):</p>
        <p>While I agree that Al Gore's choice of Joseph I. Lieberman as his running mate was a good one, I think you correctly point out that it is imperative that the Gore-Lieberman campaign and the Democratic Party not take on a tone that reminds voters of the Republicans' courtship of the religious right.</p>
        <p>Separation of church and state is an inherent concept in American ideology, and frequent references to ''God Almighty,'' regardless of the perspective of the speaker, can have the same alienating effect, whether it comes from an Orthodox Jewish senator and vice-presidential candidate cultivating the Democratic vote, or from a former Republican candidate, like Pat Robertson, appealing to a very different audience.</p>
        <p>ARON P. GOLDFELD  Plantation, Fla., Aug. 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
